# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: check-weigher
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] The terms **active packaging**, **intelligent packaging**, and **smart packaging** refer to amplified packaging systems used with foods, pharmaceuticals, and several other types of products.
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] They help extend shelf life, monitor freshness, display information on quality, improve safety, and improve convenience.
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] The terms are often related and can overlap.
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] *Active packaging* usually means having active functions beyond the inert *passive* containment and protection of the product.
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] *Intelligent* and *smart* packaging usually involve the ability to sense or measure an attribute of the product, the inner atmosphere of the package, or the shipping environment.
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] This information can be communicated to users or can trigger active packaging functions.
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] Programmable matter, smart materials, etc. can be employed in packages.
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] Depending on the working definitions, some traditional types of packaging might be considered as "active" or "intelligent".
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] More often, the terms are used with new technologically advanced systems: microelectronics, computer applications, nanotechnology, etc.
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] For many years, desiccants have been used to control the water vapor in a closed package.
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] A desiccant is a hygroscopic substance usually in a porous pouch or sachet which is placed inside a sealed package.
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] They have been used to reduce corrosion of machinery and electronics and to extend the shelf life of moisture-sensitive foods.
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] With pharmaceutical packages, a common method is to include a small packet of desiccant in a bottle.
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] Other methods of including desiccants attached to the inner surface or in the material have recently been developed.
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] Corrosion inhibitors can be applied to items to help prevent rust and corrosion.
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] Volatile corrosion inhibitors (VCI) or vapor phase corrosion inhibitors can be provided inside a package in a pouch or can be incorporated in a saturated overwrap of special paper or plastic film.
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] Many of these are organic salts that condense on the metal to resist corrosion.
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] Some films also have VCI emitting capability.
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] Films are available with copper ions in the polymer structure, These neutralize the corrosive gas in a package and deter rust.
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] VCIs create a neutral environment in the packaging.
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] It works on the principle of difference in vapour pressure and causes reaction with metals and non-metals, and with moisture to prevent corrosion.
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] There are different forms of VCIs available, such as papers, plastics, HDPE papers, oils, foams, chips, aluminum barrier foils, bubble, and emitters that can prevent corrosion at many stages.
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] Trace transition metals in foods, especially iron, can induce oxidative degradation of many food components, especially lipids, and cause quality changes of the products.
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] Metal-chelating active packaging materials are made by immobilizing metal-chelating active compounds onto traditional active packaging material.
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] The surface immobilized metal-chelating compounds can scavenge the transition metals from the product and enhance the oxidative stability of the product.
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] The metal-chelating active packaging technology is also antioxidant active packaging that will extend the shelf-life of consumer products by controlling the oxidation.
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] The metal-chelating active packaging technology is known to be able to remove synthetic food preservatives (e.g.
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] This technology can be used to address the increasing consumer demand for additive free and 'clean' label food products.
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] Oxygen scavengers or oxygen absorbers help remove oxygen from a closed package.
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] Oxygen causes acceleration of product degradation and oxidation of e.g. vitamins and fats by stimulating microbial activity.
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] As a result, poor taste, bad odor, discoloration and nutrient degradation may be the consequences.
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] Examples of an oxygen scavengers are small packets or sachets containing powdered iron: as the iron rusts, oxygen is removed from the surrounding atmosphere.
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] Other metals, such as platinum or palladium can also be used.
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] Organic oxygen scavengers can also be applied, such as tocopherols, unsaturated hydrocarbons, ascorbic acid, and oxygen scavengers based on enzymes or microorganisms.
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] Newer systems are on cards or can be built into package films or molded structures.
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] In addition, the physical characteristics of the packaging itself (oxygen transmission rate - OTR) can dictate how effective an oxygen absorber can be, and how long it will stay effective.
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] Packaging with a low OTR will let less oxygen in the closed package through the polymer barrier itself.
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] With some products, such as cheese, it has long been common to flush the package with nitrogen prior to sealing: the inert nitrogen is absorbed into the cheese, allowing a tight shrink film package.
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] The nitrogen removes oxygen and interacts with the cheese to make the package functional.
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] More recently, other mixtures of gas have been used inside the package to extend the shelf life.
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] The gas mixture depends on the specific product and its degradation mechanisms.
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] Some package components have been developed that incorporate active chemistry to help maintain certain atmospheres in packages.
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] Oxygen scavengers, carbon dioxide generators, ethanol generators, etc. are available to help keep the atmosphere in a package at specified conditions.
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] Fruits and vegetables naturally discharge ethylene, which has a critical role in the growth, ripening and germination processes.
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] In order to preserve long-term food quality, it may be desired to inhibit ethylene synthesis.
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] As such, synthesis inhibitors or scavengers can be used.
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] One of the most common ethylene scavengers is potassium permanganate (KMnO4), which is typically immobilized on siliga gel or alumina.
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] Other ethylene scavengers include activated carbon or zeolites.
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] Alternatively, 1-methylcyclopropene (1-MCP) can be used to inhibit the hormonal action of ethylene.
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] Some temperature indicators give a visual signal that a specified temperature has been exceeded.
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] Others, time temperature indicators, signal when a critical accumulation of temperature deviation over time has been exceeded.
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] When the mechanism of the indicator is tuned to the mechanism of product degradation, these can provide valuable signals for consumers.
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] Digital temperature data loggers record the temperatures encountered throughout the shipment.
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] This data can be used to predict product degradation and help determine if the product is suited for normal sale or if expedited sale is required.
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] They also determine the time of the temperature excess: this can be used to direct corrective action.
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] Thermochromic inks are sometimes used to signal temperature excess or change.
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] Some are reversible while others have a permanent change of color.
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] These can be used alone or with other packaging functions such as barcodes.
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] The inks can also signal a desired temperature for consumers.
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] For example, one type of beer can has ink that graphically shows when an ideal drinking temperature is achieved.
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] For critical vaccines, insulated shipping containers are passive packaging to help control the temperatures fluctuations seen even with a controlled cold chain.
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] In addition, gel packs are often used to keep the temperature of the contents within specified acceptable temperature ranges.
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] Some newer packages have the ability to heat or cool the product for the consumer.
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] These have segregated compartments where exothermic or endothermic reactions provide the desired effect.
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] Self-heating food packaging is available for several products.
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] Some packages have closures or other dispensing systems that change the contents from a liquid to an aerosol.
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] These are used for products ranging from precision inhalers for medications to spray bottles of household cleaners.
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] Some dispensing packages for two-part epoxy adhesives do more than passively contain the two components.
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] When dispensed, some packages meter (at the proper ratio, e.g.
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] 1:1, 1:10, …) and sometimes additionally mix the two components so the adhesive is fully functioning at the point of application (e.g. expoxy mixing tip, epoxy mixing nozzle).
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] The ability of a package to fully empty or dispense a viscous liquid is somewhat dependent on the surface energy of the inner walls of the container.
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] The use of superhydrophobic surfaces is useful but can be further improved by using new lubricant-impregnated surfaces.
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] Radio-frequency identification (RFID) chips are becoming more common with the introduction of smart labels that are used to track and trace packages and unit loads throughout distribution.
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] Newer developments include recording the temperature history of shipments and other intelligent packaging functions.
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] RFID can be integrated into labels: smart labels.
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] A variety of security printing methods, security holograms, and specialized labels are available to help confirm that the product in the package is not counterfeit.
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] RFID chips are being used in this application also.
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] Electronic article surveillance (on the product or on the package) is used to help counter shoplifting.
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] Metallised films are used as a susceptor for cooking in microwave ovens.
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] These increase the heating capacity and help make foods crisp and brown.
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] Plastic microwavable containers are also used for microwave cooking.
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] Shock detectors have been available for many years.
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] These are attached to the package or to the product in the package to determine if an excessive shock has been encountered.
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] The mechanisms of these *shock overload* devices have been spring-mass systems, magnets, drops of red dye, and several others.
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] Recently, digital shock and vibration data loggers have been available to more accurately record the shocks and vibrations of shipment.
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] These are used to monitor critical shipments to determine if extra inspection and calibration is required.
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] They are also used to monitor the types of shocks and vibrations encountered in transit for use in package testing in a laboratory.
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] Some engineered packaging films contain enzymes, antimicrobial agents, scavengers, natural pigments and other active components to help control food degradation and extend shelf life and safety.
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] The mechanism focuses on preventing the growth of pathogenic or spoilage microorganisms.
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] Meat absorbent pads meat diapers can contain antibacterials and have materials to signal contamination.
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] Bar codes have long been used with packaging to identify an item, facilitate routing, communicate locations, etc. there are many varieties of linear bar codes.
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] Some are stacked to provide more information.
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] Two dimensional Matrix codes can have a higher information density.
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] QR Codes can be used on packaging to provide additional information on the product via a smartphone scan.
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] With digital printers, unit-level QR Codes can become the equivalent of a unique identifier or URL for each packaging, and enable other interactions with consumers such as providing specific information on product traceability, or deploying loyalty programs.
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] Unit-level QR Codes are easy to counterfeit if additional security features are not used, but the scan data generated can be used for active brand protection.
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] A digital watermark or secure graphic can be inserted into the QR Code to make it copy-sensitive and let consumers authenticate products with a higher security level.
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] The GS1 digital link is a standard for embedding GS1 standardised product identifiers into the unique identifier, which allows the same QR Code (or other data carrier) to provide information to consumers, retailers and supply chain.
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] Printed codes can be combined with security printing for expanded uses.
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] For example, thermochromic ink can be used to activate, change, or deactivate a code based on the item's temperature history.
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] Edible films have been developed to allow consumers to eat the package along with the product.
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] Packaging materials including silver nanoparticles have been shown to extend the shelf life of some foods.
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] Special packaging has been developed for shipping organs which keeps them alive during extended shipments.
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] The organs are alive and fresh for transplanting.
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] Several packages used by Canadian cannabis corporations use active packaging to monitor THC levels throughout the production process.
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] This is being implemented in order to ensure consistency between products to improve supply chain management as well as offer consumers improved value of purchase.
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] Active packaging is often designed to interact with the contents of the package.
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] Thus extra care is often needed for active or smart packagings that are food contact materials.
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] Food packagers take extra care with some types of active packaging.
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] For example, when the oxygen atmosphere in a package is reduced for extending shelf life, controls for anaerobic bacteria need to be considered.
[src:check-weigher/active-packaging] Also when a controlled atmosphere reduces the appearance of food degradation, consumers need to retain a means of determining whether actual degradation is present.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] The use of adhesives offers certain advantages over other binding techniques such as sewing, mechanical fastenings, and welding.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] These include the ability to bind different materials together, the more efficient distribution of stress across a joint, the cost-effectiveness of an easily mechanized process, and greater flexibility in design.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] Disadvantages of adhesive use include decreased stability at high temperatures, relative weakness in bonding large objects with a small bonding surface area, and greater difficulty in separating objects during testing.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] Adhesives are typically organized by the method of adhesion followed by *reactive* or *non-reactive*, a term which refers to whether the adhesive chemically reacts in order to harden.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] Alternatively, they can be organized either by their starting physical phase or whether their raw stock is of natural or synthetic origin.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] Adhesives may be found naturally or produced synthetically.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] The earliest known human use of adhesive-like substances was approximately 200,000 years ago, when Neanderthals produced tar from the dry distillation of birch bark for use in binding stone tools to wooden handles.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] The first references to adhesives in literature appeared approximately 2000 BC.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] The Greeks and Romans made great contributions to the development of adhesives.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] In Europe, glue was not widely used until the period AD 1500–1700.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] From then until the 1900s increases in adhesive use and discovery were relatively gradual.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] Only since the 20th century has the development of synthetic adhesives accelerated rapidly, and innovation in the field continues to the present.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] The earliest evidence of human adhesive use was discovered in central Italy when three stone implements were discovered with birch bark tar indications.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] The tools were dated to about 200,000 before present in the Middle Paleolithic.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] It is the earliest example of tar-hafted stone tools.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] An experimental archeology study published in 2019 demonstrated how birch bark tar can be produced in an easier, more discoverable process.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] It involves directly burning birch bark under an overhanging rock surface in an open-air environment and collecting the tar that builds up on the rock.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] Although sticky enough, plant-based, single-component adhesives can be brittle and vulnerable to environmental conditions.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] The first use of compound adhesives was discovered in Sibudu, South Africa.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] Here, 70,000-year-old stone segments that were once inserted in axe hafts were discovered covered with an adhesive composed of plant gum and red ochre (natural iron oxide) as adding ochre to plant gum produces a stronger product and protects the gum from disintegrating under wet conditions.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] The ability to produce stronger adhesives allowed middle Stone Age humans to attach stone segments to sticks in greater variations, which led to the development of new tools.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] A study of material from Le Moustier indicates that Middle Paleolithic people, possibly Neanderthals, used glue made from a mixture of ocher and bitumen to make hand grips for cutting and scraping stone tools.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] More recent examples of adhesive use by prehistoric humans have been found at the burial sites of ancient tribes.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] Archaeologists studying the sites found that approximately 6,000 years ago the tribesmen had buried their dead together with food found in broken clay pots repaired with tree resins.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] Another investigation by archaeologists uncovered the use of bituminous cements to fasten ivory eyeballs to statues in Babylonian temples dating to approximately 4000 BC.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] In 2000, a paper revealed the discovery of a 5,200-year-old man nicknamed the "Tyrolean Iceman" or "Ötzi", who was preserved in a glacier near the Austria-Italy border.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] Several of his belongings were found with him including two arrows with flint arrowheads and a copper hatchet, each with evidence of organic glue used to connect the stone or metal parts to the wooden shafts.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] The glue was analyzed as pitch, which requires the heating of tar during its production.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] The retrieval of this tar requires a transformation of birch bark by means of heat, in a process known as pyrolysis.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] The first references to adhesives in literature appeared in approximately 2000 BC.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] Further historical records of adhesive use are found from the period spanning 1500–1000 BC.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] Artifacts from this period include paintings depicting wood gluing operations and a casket made of wood and glue in King Tutankhamun's tomb.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] Other ancient Egyptian artifacts employ animal glue for bonding or lamination.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] Such lamination of wood for bows and furniture is thought to have extended their life and was accomplished using casein (milk protein)-based glues.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] The ancient Egyptians also developed starch-based pastes for the bonding of papyrus to clothing and a plaster of Paris-like material made of calcined gypsum.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] From AD 1 to 500 the Greeks and Romans made great contributions to the development of adhesives.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] Wood veneering and marquetry were developed, the production of animal and fish glues refined, and other materials utilized.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] Egg-based pastes were used to bond gold leaves, and incorporated various natural ingredients such as blood, bone, hide, milk, cheese, vegetables, and grains.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] The Greeks began the use of slaked lime as mortar while the Romans furthered mortar development by mixing lime with volcanic ash and sand.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] This material, known as pozzolanic cement, was used in the construction of the Roman Colosseum and Pantheon.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] The Romans were also the first people known to have used tar and beeswax as caulk and sealant between the wooden planks of their boats and ships.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] In Central Asia, the rise of the Mongols in approximately AD 1000 can be partially attributed to the good range and power of the bows of Genghis Khan's hordes.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] These bows were made of a bamboo core, with horn on the belly (facing towards the archer) and sinew on the back, bound together with animal glue.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] In Europe, glue fell into disuse until the period AD 1500–1700.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] At this time, world-renowned cabinet and furniture makers such as Thomas Chippendale and Duncan Phyfe began to use adhesives to hold their products together.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] In 1690, the first commercial glue plant was established in The Netherlands.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] This plant produced glues from animal hides.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] In 1750, the first British glue patent was issued for fish glue.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] The following decades of the next century witnessed the manufacture of casein glues in German and Swiss factories.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] In 1876, the first U.S. patent (number 183,024) was issued to the Ross brothers for the production of casein glue.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] The first U.S. postage stamps used starch-based adhesives when issued in 1847.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] The first US patent (number 61,991) on dextrin (a starch derivative) adhesive was issued in 1867.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] Natural rubber was first used as material for adhesives in 1830, which marked the starting point of the modern adhesive.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] In 1862, a British patent (number 3288) was issued for the plating of metal with brass by electrodeposition to obtain a stronger bond to rubber.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] The development of the automobile and the need for rubber shock mounts required stronger and more durable bonds of rubber and metal.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] This spurred the development of cyclized rubber treated in strong acids.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] By 1927, this process was used to produce solvent-based thermoplastic rubber cements for metal to rubber bonding.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] Natural rubber-based sticky adhesives were first used on a backing by Henry Day (US Patent 3,965) in 1845.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] Later these kinds of adhesives were used in cloth backed surgical and electric tapes.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] By 1925, the pressure-sensitive tape industry was born.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] Today, sticky notes, Scotch Tape, and other tapes are examples of pressure-sensitive adhesives (PSA).
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] A key step in the development of synthetic plastics was the introduction of a thermoset plastic known as Bakelite phenolic in 1910.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] Within two years, phenolic resin was applied to plywood as a coating varnish.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] In the early 1930s, phenolics gained importance as adhesive resins.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] The 1920s, 1930s, and 1940s witnessed great advances in the development and production of new plastics and resins due to the First and Second World Wars.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] These advances greatly improved the development of adhesives by allowing the use of newly developed materials that exhibited a variety of properties.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] With changing needs and ever evolving technology, the development of new synthetic adhesives continues to the present.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] However, due to their low cost, natural adhesives are still more commonly used.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] Adhesives are typically organized by the method of adhesion.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] These are then organized into reactive and non-reactive adhesives, which refers to whether the adhesive chemically reacts in order to harden.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] Alternatively they can be organized by whether the raw stock is of natural or synthetic origin, or by their starting physical phase.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] There are two types of adhesives that harden by drying: *solvent-based adhesives* and *polymer dispersion adhesives*, also known as *emulsion adhesives*.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] Solvent-based adhesives are a mixture of ingredients (typically polymers) dissolved in a solvent.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] White glue, contact adhesives and rubber cements are members of the *drying adhesive* family.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] As the solvent evaporates, the adhesive hardens.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] Depending on the chemical composition of the adhesive, they will adhere to different materials to greater or lesser degrees.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] Polymer dispersion adhesives are milky-white dispersions often based on polyvinyl acetate (PVAc).
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] They are used extensively in the woodworking and packaging industries.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] They are also used with fabrics and fabric-based components, and in engineered products such as loudspeaker cones.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] PSAs are designed for either permanent or removable applications.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] Examples of permanent applications include safety labels for power equipment, foil tape for HVAC duct work, automotive interior trim assembly, and sound/vibration damping films.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] Some high performance permanent PSAs exhibit high adhesion values and can support kilograms of weight per square centimeter of contact area, even at elevated temperatures.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] Permanent PSAs may initially be removable (for example to recover mislabeled goods) and build adhesion to a permanent bond after several hours or days.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] Removable adhesives are designed to form a temporary bond, and ideally can be removed after months or years without leaving residue on the adherend.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] Some removable adhesives are designed to repeatedly stick and unstick.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] They have low adhesion, and generally cannot support much weight.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] Pressure-sensitive adhesive is used in Post-it notes.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] Pressure-sensitive adhesives are manufactured with either a liquid carrier or in 100% solid form.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] Articles are made from liquid PSAs by coating the adhesive and drying off the solvent or water carrier.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] They may be further heated to initiate a cross-linking reaction and increase molecular weight.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] 100% solid PSAs may be low viscosity polymers that are coated and then reacted with radiation to increase molecular weight and form the adhesive, or they may be high viscosity materials that are heated to reduce viscosity enough to allow coating, and then cooled to their final form.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] Major raw material for PSA's are acrylate-based polymers.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] Contact adhesives must be applied to both surfaces and allowed some time to dry before the two surfaces are pushed together.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] Some contact adhesives require as long as 24 hours to dry completely before the surfaces are to be held together.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] Once the surfaces are pushed together, the bond forms very quickly.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] Clamping is not required due to the rapid bond formation.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] Thermoplastic glue may have been invented around 1940 by Procter & Gamble as a solution to the problem that water-based adhesives, commonly used in packaging at that time, failed in humid climates, causing packages to open.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] However, water-based adhesives are still of strong interest as they typically do not contain volatile solvents.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] Anaerobic adhesives cure when in contact with metal, in the absence of oxygen.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] They work well in a close-fitting space, as when used as a thread-locking fluid.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] There are several commercial combinations of multi-component adhesives in use in industry.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] The individual components of a multi-component adhesive are not adhesive by nature.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] The individual components react with each other after being mixed and show full adhesion only on curing.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] The multi-component resins can be either solvent-based or solvent-less.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] The solvents present in the adhesives are a medium for the polyester or the polyurethane resin.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] The solvent is dried during the curing process.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] Natural adhesives are made from organic sources such as vegetable starch (dextrin), natural resins, or animals (e.g. the milk protein casein and hide-based animal glues).
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] These are often referred to as bioadhesives.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] One example is a simple paste made by cooking flour in water.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] Starch-based adhesives are used in corrugated board and paper sack production, paper tube winding, and wallpaper adhesives.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] Casein glue is mainly used to adhere glass bottle labels.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] Animal glues have traditionally been used in bookbinding, wood joining, and many other areas but now are largely replaced by synthetic glues except in specialist applications like the production and repair of stringed instruments.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] Albumen made from the protein component of blood has been used in the plywood industry.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] Masonite, a wood hardboard, was originally bonded using natural wood lignin, an organic polymer, though most modern particle boards such as MDF use synthetic thermosetting resins.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] Synthetic adhesives are made out of organic compounds.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] Many are based on elastomers, thermoplastics, emulsions, and thermosets.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] Examples of thermosetting adhesives are: epoxy, polyurethane, cyanoacrylate and acrylic polymers.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] The first commercially produced synthetic adhesive was Karlsons Klister in the 1920s.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] Applicators of different adhesives are designed according to the adhesive being used and the size of the area to which the adhesive will be applied.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] The adhesive is applied to either one or both of the materials being bonded.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] The pieces are aligned and pressure is added to aid in adhesion and rid the bond of air bubbles.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] Common ways of applying an adhesive include brushes, rollers, using films or pellets, spray guns and applicator guns (*e.g.*, caulk gun).
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] All of these can be used manually or automated as part of a machine.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] For an adhesive to be effective it must have three main properties.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] Firstly, it must be able to wet the base material.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] Wetting is the ability of a liquid to maintain contact with a solid surface.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] It must also increase in strength after application, and finally it must be able to transmit load between the two surfaces/substrates being adhered.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] Adhesion, the attachment between adhesive and substrate may occur either by mechanical means, in which the adhesive works its way into small pores of the substrate, or by one of several chemical mechanisms.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] The strength of adhesion depends on many factors, including the means by which it occurs.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] In some cases, an actual chemical bond occurs between adhesive and substrate.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] Thiolated polymers, for example, form chemical bonds with endogenous proteins such as mucus glycoproteins, integrins or keratins via disulfide bridges.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] Because of their comparatively high adhesive properties, these polymers find numerous biomedical applications.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] In others, electrostatic forces, as in static electricity, hold the substances together.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] A third mechanism involves the van der Waals forces that develop between molecules.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] A fourth means involves the moisture-aided diffusion of the glue into the substrate, followed by hardening.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] The quality of adhesive bonding depends strongly on the ability of the adhesive to efficiently cover (wet) the substrate area.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] This happens when the surface energy of the substrate is greater than the surface energy of the adhesive.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] However, high-strength adhesives have high surface energy.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] Thus, they bond poorly to low-surface-energy polymers or other materials.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] To solve this problem, surface treatment can be used to increase the surface energy as a preparation step before adhesive bonding.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] Importantly, surface preparation provides a reproducible surface allowing consistent bonding results.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] The commonly used surface activation techniques include plasma activation, flame treatment and wet chemistry priming.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] Adhesives can be designed so that they debond when an electric current or electric field is applied, thereby eliminating part damage, or the need for heating.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] Depending on the type of adhesive, different health risks present themselves.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] Exposure can occur by direct contact or inhalation of fumes and is potentially life-threatening.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] There are several factors that could contribute to the failure of two adhered surfaces.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] Sunlight and heat may weaken the adhesive.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] Solvents can deteriorate or dissolve adhesive.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] Physical stresses may also cause the separation of surfaces.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] When subjected to loading, debonding may occur at different locations in the adhesive joint.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] As a general design rule, the material properties of the object need to be greater than the forces anticipated during its use.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] The engineering work will consist of having a good model to evaluate the function.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] For most adhesive joints, this can be achieved using fracture mechanics.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] Concepts such as the stress concentration factor and the strain energy release rate can be used to predict failure.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] In such models, the behavior of the adhesive layer itself is neglected and only the adherents are considered.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] Failure will also very much depend on the opening *mode* of the joint.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] As the loads are usually fixed, an acceptable design will result from combination of a material selection procedure and geometry modifications, if possible.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] In adhesively bonded structures, the global geometry and loads are fixed by structural considerations and the design procedure focuses on the material properties of the adhesive and on local changes on the geometry.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] Some glues and adhesives have a limited shelf life.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] Shelf life is dependent on multiple factors, the foremost of which being temperature.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] Adhesives may lose their effectiveness at high temperatures, as well as become increasingly stiff.
[src:check-weigher/adhesive] Other factors affecting shelf life include exposure to oxygen or water vapor.
[src:check-weigher/aerosol-spray-dispenser] There is a high chance that the concepts of aerosol go as far back as 1790.
[src:check-weigher/aerosol-spray-dispenser] The first aerosol spray can patent was granted in Oslo in 1927 to Erik Rotheim, a Norwegian chemical engineer, and a United States patent was granted for the invention in 1931.
[src:check-weigher/aerosol-spray-dispenser] The patent rights were sold to a United States company for 100,000 Norwegian kroner.
[src:check-weigher/aerosol-spray-dispenser] The Norwegian Postal Service, Posten Norge, celebrated the invention by issuing a stamp in 1998.
[src:check-weigher/aerosol-spray-dispenser] Kahn received a patent for a disposable spray can, but the product remained largely undeveloped.
[src:check-weigher/aerosol-spray-dispenser] Kahn's idea was to mix cream and a propellant from two sources to make whipped cream at home—not a true aerosol in that sense.
[src:check-weigher/aerosol-spray-dispenser] Moreover, in 1949, he disclaimed his first four claims, which were the foundation of his following patent claims.
[src:check-weigher/aerosol-spray-dispenser] It was not until 1941 that the aerosol spray can was first put to effective use by Americans Lyle Goodhue and William Sullivan of the United States Bureau of Entomology and Plant Quarantine, who are credited as the inventors of the modern spray can.
[src:check-weigher/aerosol-spray-dispenser] Their design of a refillable spray can, dubbed the **aerosol bomb** or **bug bomb**, is the ancestor of many commercial spray products.
[src:check-weigher/aerosol-spray-dispenser] It was a hand-sized steel can charged with a liquefied gas under 75 pounds of pressure and a product to be expelled as a mist or a foam.
[src:check-weigher/aerosol-spray-dispenser] A public-service patent was issued on the invention and assigned to the Secretary of Agriculture for the free use of the people of the United States.
[src:check-weigher/aerosol-spray-dispenser] Pressurized by liquefied gas, which gave it propellant qualities, the small, portable can enabled soldiers to defend themselves against malaria-carrying mosquitoes by spraying inside tents and airplanes in the Pacific during World War II.
[src:check-weigher/aerosol-spray-dispenser] Goodhue and Sullivan received the first Erik Rotheim Gold Medal from the Federation of European Aerosol Associations on August 28, 1970, in Oslo, Norway in recognition of their early patents and subsequent pioneering work with aerosol sprays.
[src:check-weigher/aerosol-spray-dispenser] In 1948, three companies were granted licenses by the United States government to manufacture aerosol sprays.
[src:check-weigher/aerosol-spray-dispenser] Two of the three companies, Chase Products Company and Claire Manufacturing, continue to manufacture aerosol sprays.
[src:check-weigher/aerosol-spray-dispenser] The "crimp-on valve", used to control the spray in low-pressure aerosol sprays was developed in 1949 by Bronx machine shop proprietor Robert H.
[src:check-weigher/aerosol-spray-dispenser] Molina proposed that chlorofluorocarbons, used as propellants in aerosol sprays, contributed to the depletion of Earth's ozone layer.
[src:check-weigher/aerosol-spray-dispenser] Congress passed amendments to the Clean Air Act in 1977 authorizing the Environmental Protection Agency to regulate the presence of CFCs in the atmosphere.
[src:check-weigher/aerosol-spray-dispenser] The United Nations Environment Programme called for ozone layer research that same year, and, in 1981, authorized a global framework convention on ozone layer protection.
[src:check-weigher/aerosol-spray-dispenser] Gardiner, and Jon Shanklin published the first scientific paper detailing the hole in the ozone layer.
[src:check-weigher/aerosol-spray-dispenser] That same year, the Vienna Convention was signed in response to the UN's authorization.
[src:check-weigher/aerosol-spray-dispenser] Two years later, the Montreal Protocol, which regulated the production of CFCs was formally signed.
[src:check-weigher/aerosol-spray-dispenser] The U.S. formally phased out CFCs in 1995.
[src:check-weigher/aerosol-spray-dispenser] If aerosol cans were simply filled with compressed gas, it would either need to be at a dangerously high pressure and require special pressure vessel design (like in gas cylinders), or the amount of payload in the can would be small, and rapidly deplete.
[src:check-weigher/aerosol-spray-dispenser] Usually, the gas is the vapor of a liquid with boiling point slightly lower than room temperature.
[src:check-weigher/aerosol-spray-dispenser] This means that inside the pressurized can, the vapor can exist in equilibrium with its bulk liquid at a pressure that is higher than atmospheric pressure (and able to expel the payload), but not dangerously high.
[src:check-weigher/aerosol-spray-dispenser] As gas escapes, it is immediately replaced by evaporating liquid.
[src:check-weigher/aerosol-spray-dispenser] Since the propellant exists in liquid form in the can, it should be miscible with the payload or dissolved in the payload.
[src:check-weigher/aerosol-spray-dispenser] In gas dusters and freeze sprays, the payload itself acts as the propellant.
[src:check-weigher/aerosol-spray-dispenser] The propellant in a gas duster can is not "compressed air" as sometimes assumed, but usually a haloalkane.
[src:check-weigher/aerosol-spray-dispenser] Chlorofluorocarbons (CFCs) were once often used as propellants, but since the Montreal Protocol came into force in 1989, they have been replaced in nearly every country due to the negative effects CFCs have on Earth's ozone layer.
[src:check-weigher/aerosol-spray-dispenser] The most common replacements of CFCs are mixtures of volatile hydrocarbons, typically propane, n-butane and isobutane.
[src:check-weigher/aerosol-spray-dispenser] Dimethyl ether (DME) and methyl ethyl ether are also used.
[src:check-weigher/aerosol-spray-dispenser] All these have the disadvantage of being flammable.
[src:check-weigher/aerosol-spray-dispenser] Nitrous oxide and carbon dioxide are also used as propellants to deliver foodstuffs (for example, whipped cream and cooking spray).
[src:check-weigher/aerosol-spray-dispenser] Medicinal aerosols such as asthma inhalers use hydrofluoroalkanes (HFA): either HFA 134a (1,1,1,2,-tetrafluoroethane) or HFA 227 (1,1,1,2,3,3,3-heptafluoropropane) or combinations of the two.
[src:check-weigher/aerosol-spray-dispenser] More recently, liquid hydrofluoroolefin (HFO) propellants have become more widely adopted in aerosol systems due to their relatively low vapor pressure, low global warming potential (GWP), and nonflammability.
[src:check-weigher/aerosol-spray-dispenser] Liquid aerosol propellant filling machines require additional precautions, such as being mounted externally to the production warehouse in a gas house.
[src:check-weigher/aerosol-spray-dispenser] Liquid aerosol propellant machines are typically constructed to comply with ATEX Zone II/2G regulations (classification Zone 1).
[src:check-weigher/aerosol-spray-dispenser] Modern aerosol spray products have three major parts: the can, the valve and the actuator or button.
[src:check-weigher/aerosol-spray-dispenser] The can is most commonly lacquered tinplate (steel with a layer of tin) and may be made of two or three pieces of metal crimped together.
[src:check-weigher/aerosol-spray-dispenser] Aluminium cans are also common and are generally used for products that are more expensive or intended to have a more premium appearance, such as personal care products.
[src:check-weigher/aerosol-spray-dispenser] The valve is crimped to the inside rim of the can, and the design of this component is important in determining the spray rate.
[src:check-weigher/aerosol-spray-dispenser] The actuator is depressed by the user to open the valve; a spring closes the valve again when it is released.
[src:check-weigher/aerosol-spray-dispenser] The shape and size of the nozzle in the actuator controls the aerosolized particle size and the spread of the aerosol spray.
[src:check-weigher/aerosol-spray-dispenser] True aerosol sprays release their propellant during use.
[src:check-weigher/aerosol-spray-dispenser] Some non-propellant alternatives include various spray bottles, squeeze bottles, and Bag on Valve (BoV) or Bag in Can (BiC) compressed gas aerosol systems.
[src:check-weigher/aerosol-spray-dispenser] Packaging that uses a piston barrier system by CCL Industries or EarthSafe by Crown Holdings is often selected for highly viscous products such as post-foaming hair gels, thick creams and lotions, food spreads and industrial products and sealants.
[src:check-weigher/aerosol-spray-dispenser] The main benefit of this system is that it eliminates gas permeation and assures separation of the product from the propellant, maintaining the purity and integrity of the formulation throughout its consumer lifespan.
[src:check-weigher/aerosol-spray-dispenser] The piston barrier system also provides a consistent flow rate with minimal product retention.
[src:check-weigher/aerosol-spray-dispenser] Another type of dispensing system is the bag-in-can (or BOV, bag-on-valve technology) system where the product is separated from the pressurizing agent with a hermetically sealed, multi-layered laminated pouch, which maintains complete formulation integrity so only pure product is dispensed.
[src:check-weigher/aerosol-spray-dispenser] Among its many benefits, the bag-in-can system extends a product's shelf life, is suitable for all-attitude, (360-degree) dispensing, quiet and non-chilling discharge.
[src:check-weigher/aerosol-spray-dispenser] One key performance difference relative to true aerosol systems is that traditional BoV dispensing pressures, BoVs pressurized solely by pressurized gas) drops as the product is dispensed.
[src:check-weigher/aerosol-spray-dispenser] This bag-in-can system is used in the packaging of pharmaceutical, industrial, household, pet care and other products that require complete separation between the product and the propellant or require near complete evacuation of thin to viscous formulations.
[src:check-weigher/aerosol-spray-dispenser] A later development is the 2K (two component) aerosol spray, with a main component stored in a main chamber, and a second component stored in an accessory container.
[src:check-weigher/aerosol-spray-dispenser] When an applicator activates the 2K aerosol by breaking the accessory container, the two components mix.
[src:check-weigher/aerosol-spray-dispenser] The 2K aerosol can is advantageous for delivery of reactive mixtures; for example, a 2K reactive mixture can use low molecular weight monomer, oligomer, and functionalized low molecular polymer to make a final cross-linked high molecular weight polymer.
[src:check-weigher/aerosol-spray-dispenser] A 2K aerosol can increase solid contents and deliver high-performance polymer products, such as curable paints, foams, and adhesives.
[src:check-weigher/aerosol-spray-dispenser] In the United States, non-empty aerosol cans are considered hazardous waste, but are still considered "recyclable when empty" in US curbside recycling programs.
[src:check-weigher/aerosol-spray-dispenser] Aerosol products in the European Union must comply with health and safety regulations as set out in Directive 75/324/EEC. which established the "**reversed epsilon**" mark.
[src:check-weigher/aerosol-spray-dispenser] This marking is required for aerosol products over 50ml.
[src:check-weigher/aerosol-spray-dispenser] The same marking is also used in the United Kingdom, although the UKCA marking is planned to replace it in Great Britain.
[src:check-weigher/alternative-wine-closure] The cork-industry group APCOR cites a study showing a 0.7–1.2% taint rate.
[src:check-weigher/alternative-wine-closure] In a 2005 study of 2800 bottles tasted at the *Wine Spectator* blind-tasting facilities in Napa, California, 7% of the bottles were found to be tainted.
[src:check-weigher/alternative-wine-closure] Synthetic corks are made from plastic compounds designed to look and "pop" like natural cork, but without the risk of TCA contamination.
[src:check-weigher/alternative-wine-closure] Disadvantages of synthetic corks include a risk of harmful air entering a bottle after as little as 18 months, difficulty in extracting them from the bottle, and difficulty in using the cork to reseal the wine.
[src:check-weigher/alternative-wine-closure] James Laube of *Wine Spectator* notes that some can also impart a slight chemical flavour to the wine.
[src:check-weigher/alternative-wine-closure] Unlike natural corks, many synthetic corks are made from material that is not biodegradable.
[src:check-weigher/alternative-wine-closure] There are two main production techniques for synthetic wine closures: injection molding and extrusion.
[src:check-weigher/alternative-wine-closure] There are also methods claimed to combine the two techniques of injection and extrusion.
[src:check-weigher/alternative-wine-closure] A 2007 study by Victor Segalen Bordeaux 2 University showed that injection-molded synthetic corks allowed the highest levels of oxygen permeation when compared to natural cork and screw caps, offering the lowest protection against oxidation of the wine.
[src:check-weigher/alternative-wine-closure] Synthetic wine bottle closures may allow for a controlled oxygen transfer rate, which affects the sensory characteristics.
[src:check-weigher/alternative-wine-closure] Screw caps or "Stelvin caps" are closures made only from aluminium material that threads onto the bottleneck.
[src:check-weigher/alternative-wine-closure] They are the predominant closure used by Austrian, Australian and New Zealand wineries.
[src:check-weigher/alternative-wine-closure] This can be attributed in part to the New Zealand screw cap initiative which promotes the use of screw caps instead of cork.
[src:check-weigher/alternative-wine-closure] Screw caps form a tighter seal and can keep out oxygen for a longer time than cork.
[src:check-weigher/alternative-wine-closure] These benefits aid in maintaining the wine's overall quality and aging potential.
[src:check-weigher/alternative-wine-closure] Michel Laroche of Domaine Laroche noted that this played a role in his decision to adopt screwcaps.
[src:check-weigher/alternative-wine-closure] An often cited contradiction is the case of experiments carried out by Château Haut-Brion in the 1970s, when 100 bottles were placed under screwcap for long term observation.
[src:check-weigher/alternative-wine-closure] The result was, according to Haut-Brion manager Jean-Bernard Delmas, that "it worked perfectly for the first ten years, until the plastic in the caps went brittle and let air in".
[src:check-weigher/alternative-wine-closure] A disadvantage of screw caps according to wine expert Jancis Robinson is the opposite of oxidation: reduction, which may suppress a wine's aroma and possibly cause unpleasant ones, a problem that particularly affects Sauvignon blanc which is a grape variety with natural tendencies toward reduction.
[src:check-weigher/alternative-wine-closure] Furthermore, there is the screwcap's public image, as "consumers still perceive screwcaps as being for 'cheap' wines (regardless of the price tag)".
[src:check-weigher/alternative-wine-closure] In a 2004 study of consumer opinions conducted by the wine consulting firm Wine Intelligence found that nearly 52% of American consumers and 60% of British consumers reject the idea of using screwcaps for their fine wine.
[src:check-weigher/alternative-wine-closure] The 2007 Victor Segalen University study in Bordeaux showed that screw caps closures allowed the lowest amount of oxygen permeation when compared to natural and synthetic corks, offering the highest level of protection against oxidation of the wine.
[src:check-weigher/alternative-wine-closure] Following studies by the faults clinic at the International Wine Challenge in September 2006, it became widely reported in British newspapers that test results show that one in 50 screwcap bottles, 200,000 bottles worldwide, may be affected by the chemical process sulphidisation.
[src:check-weigher/alternative-wine-closure] Jamie Goode presented arguments against reports he described to "represent the science of closures badly, are filled with inaccuracies and misunderstandings, and do not serve the wine industry well", and addressed the inaccuracies in specific points.
[src:check-weigher/alternative-wine-closure] Vino-Seal, also sold as Vinolok, is a plastic/glass closure originally developed by Alcoa and now produced by Czech crystal glass producer Preciosa.
[src:check-weigher/alternative-wine-closure] Since its introduction into the European market in 2003, over 300 wineries have utilized the closure.
[src:check-weigher/alternative-wine-closure] Using a glass stopper with an inert o-ring, the closure is claimed to create a hermetic seal that prevents oxidation and TCA contamination.
[src:check-weigher/alternative-wine-closure] A disadvantage of the closure is the relatively high cost of each plug (70 cents each) and cost either of manual bottling, or else obtaining compatible bottling equipment.
[src:check-weigher/alternative-wine-closure] Zork is an alternative wine closure for still wines, that seals like a screw cap and pops like a cork, created by an Australian company of the same name.
[src:check-weigher/alternative-wine-closure] The closure has three parts: an outer cap providing a tamper-evident clamp that locks onto the band of a standard cork mouth bottle; an inner metal foil which provides an oxygen barrier similar to a screw cap, and an inner plunger which creates the ‘pop’ on extraction and reseals after use.
[src:check-weigher/alternative-wine-closure] Introduced in 2010, it is the first on-bottle, resealable closure for sparkling wines.
[src:check-weigher/alternative-wine-closure] There is continuing opposition to the use of alternative closures in some parts of the winemaking industry.
[src:check-weigher/alternative-wine-closure] In March 2006, the Spanish government outlawed the use of alternative wine closures in 11 of Spain's wine-producing regions as part of their (*Denominación de Origen*) D.O. regulations.
[src:check-weigher/alternative-wine-closure] Although environmentalists lament the loss of cork forests to commercial crops such as eucalyptus, advocates of artificial corks claim that "natural corks" are just "granules and dust bonded with solvents", and no more biodegradable than the artificial product.
[src:check-weigher/alternative-wine-closure] "Granules and dust bonded with solvents" describes "agglomerate corks." These differ from "natural corks" that are one piece made out of cork bark.
[src:check-weigher/aluminium-bottle] An **aluminium bottle**, also sometimes called a **bottlecan**, is a bottle made of aluminium.
[src:check-weigher/aluminium-bottle] Aluminium bottles are made through an impact extrusion process.
[src:check-weigher/aluminium-bottle] The aluminium bottle was introduced to the North American beverage market in the fall of 2001, as an alternative to plastic bottles by Coca-Cola under the Powerade brand (Psych and Raize) at the National Association of Convenience Stores Show.
[src:check-weigher/aluminium-bottle] A study conducted by engineering science students at Loyola College in Maryland suggested that the liquid content of aluminium bottles stays slightly colder than the liquid content of glass bottles, when allowed to warm at room temperature.
[src:check-weigher/aluminium-foil] Approximately 75% of aluminium foil is used for packaging of foods, cosmetics, and chemical products, and 25% is used for industrial applications (e.g., thermal insulation, electrical cables, and electronics).
[src:check-weigher/aluminium-foil] Aluminium foil supplanted tin foil in the mid-20th century.
[src:check-weigher/aluminium-foil] In the United Kingdom and United States it is often informally called "tin foil", just as steel cans are often still called "tin cans".
[src:check-weigher/aluminium-foil] Metallised films are sometimes mistaken for aluminium foil, but are actually polymer films coated with a thin layer of aluminium.
[src:check-weigher/aluminium-foil] Foil made from a thin leaf of tin was commercially available before its aluminium counterpart.
[src:check-weigher/aluminium-foil] Tin foil was marketed commercially from the late nineteenth into the early twentieth century.
[src:check-weigher/aluminium-foil] The term "tin foil" survives in the English language as a term for the newer aluminium foil.
[src:check-weigher/aluminium-foil] Tin foil is less malleable than aluminium foil and tends to give a slight tin taste to food wrapped in it.
[src:check-weigher/aluminium-foil] Tin foil has been supplanted by aluminium and other materials for wrapping food.
[src:check-weigher/aluminium-foil] The first audio recordings on phonograph cylinders were made on tin foil.
[src:check-weigher/aluminium-foil] Tin was first replaced by aluminium in 1910, when the first aluminium foil rolling plant, Dr.
[src:check-weigher/aluminium-foil] Lauber, Neher & Cie. was opened in Emmishofen, Switzerland.
[src:check-weigher/aluminium-foil] Neher & Sons, the aluminium manufacturers, was founded in 1886 in Schaffhausen, Switzerland, at the foot of the Rhine Falls, whose energy powered the process.
[src:check-weigher/aluminium-foil] In December 1907, Neher's sons, along with Dr.
[src:check-weigher/aluminium-foil] Lauber, had invented the endless rolling process, by which they discovered that aluminium foil could be used as a protective barrier.
[src:check-weigher/aluminium-foil] Bern-based Tobler began wrapping its chocolate bars in aluminium foil in 1911, including the unique triangular chocolate bar, Toblerone.
[src:check-weigher/aluminium-foil] Aluminium foil has a thickness less than 0.2 mm (7.9 mils); thinner gauges down to 6 μm (0.24 mils) are also commonly used.
[src:check-weigher/aluminium-foil] Standard household foil is typically 0.016 mm (0.63 mils) thick, and heavy-duty household foil is typically 0.024 mm (0.94 mils).
[src:check-weigher/aluminium-foil] Foil may have a non-stick coating on only one side.
[src:check-weigher/aluminium-foil] Although aluminium is non-magnetic, it is a good conductor, so even a thin sheet reflects almost all of an incident electric wave.
[src:check-weigher/aluminium-foil] At frequencies more than 100 MHz, the transmitted electric field is attenuated by more than 80 decibels (dB), that is less than 10−8 = 0.00000001 of the power gets through.
[src:check-weigher/aluminium-foil] Thin sheets of aluminium are not very effective at attenuating low-frequency magnetic fields.
[src:check-weigher/aluminium-foil] The shielding effectiveness is dependent upon the skin depth.
[src:check-weigher/aluminium-foil] A field travelling through one skin depth will lose about 63% of its energy (it is attenuated to 1/*e* = 1/2.718... of its original energy).
[src:check-weigher/aluminium-foil] Thin shields also have internal reflections that reduce the shielding effectiveness.
[src:check-weigher/aluminium-foil] The continuous casting method is much less energy-intensive and has become the preferred process.
[src:check-weigher/aluminium-foil] After the rollers, the two sheets are separated, which produces foil with one shiny side and one matte side.
[src:check-weigher/aluminium-foil] The two sides in contact with each other are matte, and the exterior sides become shiny.
[src:check-weigher/aluminium-foil] The difference in thermal properties between the two sides is imperceptible without instrumentation.
[src:check-weigher/aluminium-foil] By Kirchhoff's law of radiation, increased reflectivity decreases both absorption and emission of radiation.
[src:check-weigher/aluminium-foil] Aluminium foil is available in various types, classified by thickness, alloy composition, manufacturing process, and surface treatment.
[src:check-weigher/aluminium-foil] The most common classification is by thickness (or gauge), which determines the foil's strength, flexibility, and application.
[src:check-weigher/aluminium-foil] Other distinctions are based on temper, surface finish, and intended use.
[src:check-weigher/aluminium-foil] The thickness of aluminium foil is typically measured in microns (μm) or mils (thousandths of an inch).
[src:check-weigher/aluminium-foil] Aluminium foil is widely sold into the consumer market, such as for wrapping leftovers to be stored in a refrigerator or barbecuing delicate foods.
[src:check-weigher/aluminium-foil] As with all metallic items, it reacts to being placed in a microwave oven.
[src:check-weigher/aluminium-foil] This is because of the electromagnetic fields of the microwaves inducing electric currents in the foil and high potentials at the sharp points of the foil sheet; if the potential is sufficiently high, it will cause electric arcing to areas with lower potential, even to the air surrounding the sheet.
[src:check-weigher/aluminium-foil] Modern microwave ovens have been designed to prevent damage to the cavity magnetron tube from microwave energy reflection, and aluminium packages designed for microwave heating are available.
[src:check-weigher/aluminium-foil] Submerged in a baking soda solution, it can be used to polish metals such as silver and gold via electrolytic cleaning, as it is a more reactive metal than either.
[src:check-weigher/aluminium-foil] A similar method can be used to produce silver substrates for Raman spectrography.
[src:check-weigher/aluminium-foil] Some aluminium foil products can be recycled at around 5% of the original energy cost.
[src:check-weigher/aluminum-can] An **aluminum can** (British English: **aluminium can**) is a single-use container for packaging made primarily of an aluminum exterior with an epoxy resin or polymer coated interior.
[src:check-weigher/aluminum-can] It is commonly used for food and beverages such as olives and soup but also for products such as oil, chemicals, and other liquids.
[src:check-weigher/aluminum-can] Global production is 180 billion annually and constitutes the largest single use of aluminum globally.
[src:check-weigher/aluminum-can] Aluminum offers greater malleability, resulting in ease of manufacture; this gave rise to the two-piece can, where all but the top of the can is simply stamped out of a single piece of aluminum, rather than constructed from two pieces of steel.
[src:check-weigher/aluminum-can] The inside of the can is lined by spray coating an epoxy lacquer or polymer to protect the aluminum from being corroded by acidic contents such as carbonated beverages and imparting a metallic taste to the beverage.
[src:check-weigher/aluminum-can] A label is either printed directly on the side of the can or will be glued to the outside of the curved surface, indicating its contents.
[src:check-weigher/aluminum-can] Most aluminum cans are made of two pieces.
[src:check-weigher/aluminum-can] The bottom and body are "drawn" or "drawn and ironed" from a flat plate or shallow cup.
[src:check-weigher/aluminum-can] After filling, the can "end" is sealed onto the top of the can.
[src:check-weigher/aluminum-can] This is supplemented by a sealing compound to ensure that the top is air tight.
[src:check-weigher/aluminum-can] The easy-open aluminum end for beverage cans was developed by Alcoa in 1962 for the Pittsburgh Brewing Company and is now used in nearly all of the canned beer market.
[src:check-weigher/aluminum-can] Aluminum cans can be made with recycled aluminum.
[src:check-weigher/aluminum-can] In 2017, 3.8 million tons of aluminum were generated in the US of which 0.62 million tons were recycled - a recycling rate of 16%.
[src:check-weigher/aluminum-can] According to estimates from the Aluminum Association, a large amount of aluminium remains unrecycled in the US, where roughly $700 million worth of cans end up in landfills each year.
[src:check-weigher/aluminum-can] In 2012, 92% of the aluminum beverage cans sold in Switzerland were recycled.
[src:check-weigher/aluminum-can] Cans are the most recycled beverage container, at a rate of 69% worldwide.
[src:check-weigher/aluminum-can] One issue is that the top of the can is made from a blend of aluminum and magnesium to increase its strength.
[src:check-weigher/aluminum-can] When the can is melted for recycling, the mixture is unsuitable for either the top or the bottom/side.
[src:check-weigher/aluminum-can] Instead of mixing recycled metal with more aluminum (to soften it) or magnesium (to harden it), a new approach uses annealing to produce an alloy that works for both.
[src:check-weigher/aluminum-can] The aluminum can is also considered the most valuable recyclable material in an average recycling bin.
[src:check-weigher/aluminum-can] It is estimated that Americans throw away nearly 1 billion dollars a year in wasted aluminum.
[src:check-weigher/aluminum-can] The aluminum industry pays nearly 800 million dollars a year for recycled aluminum since it is so versatile.
[src:check-weigher/aluminum-can] Because of the advantages of aluminium packaging (shelf life, durability, food grade factor) over plastics, it is considered an alternative to PET bottles, with the possibility of replacing the majority of them in the next decades.
[src:check-weigher/aluminum-can] Can collections can be exclusive to one sector only, eg., some collectors may collect soda cans only, while others may dedicate themselves to collecting beer cans or oil cans exclusively, but some collectors may collect cans regardless of the type of can.
[src:check-weigher/aluminum-can] One aspect that may make someone interested in building a can collection as a hobby is the variety of cans available worldwide promoting such things as films, musical albums and tours, sporting teams and events, countries, ideals and even some non-food or petrol-oriented brands and companies.
[src:check-weigher/aluminum-can] Celebrities can also be featured on collectible cans; such was the case of tennis player Andre Agassi, who had a set of four Pepsi Max soda cans dedicated to him in 1996.
[src:check-weigher/aluminum-can] Davide Andreani of Italy is in the Guinness Book of World Records for having the largest collection of soda cans of one specific brand in the world, with over 20,000 cans in his collection.
[src:check-weigher/aluminum-can] Christensen of the United States owning the largest collection of beer cans with 75,000 from 125 countries and Allan Green, of the United States also, with the largest collection of wine cans, at 449.
[src:check-weigher/aluminum-can] Some webpages are dedicated to the hobby of can collecting.
[src:check-weigher/check-weigher] A **checkweigher** is an automatic or manual machine for checking the weight of packaged commodities.
[src:check-weigher/check-weigher] It is normally found at the offgoing end of a production process and is used to ensure that the weight of a pack of the commodity is within specified limits.
[src:check-weigher/check-weigher] Any packs that are outside the tolerance are taken out of line automatically.
[src:check-weigher/check-weigher] A checkweigher can weigh in excess of 500 items per minute (depending on carton size and accuracy requirements).
[src:check-weigher/check-weigher] Checkweighers can be used with metal detectors and X-ray machines to enable other attributes of the pack to be checked and acted upon accordingly.
[src:check-weigher/check-weigher] An automatic checkweigher incorporates a series of conveyor belts.
[src:check-weigher/check-weigher] These checkweighers are known also as belt weighers, in-motion scales, conveyor scales, dynamic scales, and in-line scales.
[src:check-weigher/check-weigher] In filler applications, they are known as check scales.
[src:check-weigher/check-weigher] For high-speed precision scales, a load cell using electromagnetic force restoration (EMFR) is appropriate.
[src:check-weigher/check-weigher] This kind of system charges an inductive coil, effectively floating the weigh bed in an electromagnetic field.
[src:check-weigher/check-weigher] When the weight is added, the movement of a ferrous material through that coil causes a fluctuation in the coil current proportional to the weight of the object.
[src:check-weigher/check-weigher] Other technologies used include strain gauges and vibrating wire load cells.
[src:check-weigher/check-weigher] It is usual for a built-in computer to take many weight readings from the transducer over the time that the package is on the weigh bed to ensure an accurate weight reading.
[src:check-weigher/check-weigher] A lab scale, which usually is in an isolated chamber pressurized with dry nitrogen (pressurized at sea level) can weigh an object within plus or minus 100th of a gram, but ambient air pressure is a factor.
[src:check-weigher/check-weigher] This is straightforward when there is no motion, but in motion there is a factor that is not obvious-noise from the motion of a weigh belt, vibration, air-conditioning or refrigeration which can cause drafts.
[src:check-weigher/check-weigher] Torque on a load cell causes erratic readings.
[src:check-weigher/check-weigher] A dynamic, in-motion checkweigher takes samples, and analyzes them to form an accurate weight over a given time period.
[src:check-weigher/check-weigher] In most cases, there is a trigger from an optical (or ultrasonic) device to signal the passing of a package.
[src:check-weigher/check-weigher] Once the trigger fires, there is a delay set to allow the package to move to the "sweet spot" (center) of the weigh bed to sample the weight.
[src:check-weigher/check-weigher] The weight is sampled for a given duration.
[src:check-weigher/check-weigher] If either of these times are wrong, the weight will be wrong.
[src:check-weigher/check-weigher] There seems to be no scientific method to predict these timings.
[src:check-weigher/check-weigher] Some systems have a "graphing" feature to do this, but it is generally more of an empirical method that works best.
[src:check-weigher/check-weigher] There is also a requirement under the European Average Weight System that data collected by checkweighers is archived and is available for inspection.
[src:check-weigher/check-weigher] Most modern checkweighers are therefore equipped with communications ports to enable the actual pack weights and derived data to be uploaded to a host computer.
[src:check-weigher/check-weigher] This data can also be used for management information enabling processes to be fine-tuned and production performance monitored.
[src:check-weigher/check-weigher] Checkweighers that are equipped with high speed communications such as Ethernet ports are capable of integrating themselves into groups such that a group of production lines that are producing identical products can be considered as one production line for the purposes of weight control.
[src:check-weigher/check-weigher] For example, a line that is running with a low average weight can be complemented by another that is running with a high average weight such that the aggregate of the two lines will still comply with rules.
[src:check-weigher/check-weigher] An alternative is to program the checkweigher to check bands of different weight tolerances.
[src:check-weigher/check-weigher] For instance, the total valid weight is 100 grams ±15 grams.
[src:check-weigher/check-weigher] This means that the product can weigh 85 g to 115 g.
[src:check-weigher/check-weigher] However, if 10,000 packs a day are being produced, and most are 110 g, 100 kg of product is being lost.
[src:check-weigher/check-weigher] If it is run closer to 85 g, there may be a high rejection rate.
[src:check-weigher/check-weigher] With a check weigher programmed as a zone checkweigher, the data collection over the networks, as well as local statistics, can indicate the need to check the settings on the upstream equipment to better control flow into the packaging.
[src:check-weigher/check-weigher] In some cases the dynamic scale sends a signal to a filler, for instance, in real-time, controlling the actual flow into a barrel, can, bag, etc.
[src:check-weigher/check-weigher] In many cases a checkweigher has a light-tree with different lights to indicate the variation of the zone weight of each product.
[src:check-weigher/check-weigher] This data can be used to determine if an issue exists with an upstream filling, or packaging, machine.
[src:check-weigher/check-weigher] A checkweigher can send a signal to the machine to increase or decrease the amount put into a package.
[src:check-weigher/check-weigher] This can result in a payback associated with the checkweigher since producers will be better able to control the amount of give-away.
[src:check-weigher/check-weigher] See checkweigher case study outlining ground beef and packaging savings.
[src:check-weigher/check-weigher] In-motion scales are dynamic machines that can be designed to perform thousands of tasks.
[src:check-weigher/check-weigher] Some are used as simple case weighers at the end of the conveyor line to ensure the overall finished package product is within its target weight.
[src:check-weigher/check-weigher] An in motion conveyor checkweigher can be used to detect missing pieces of a kit, such as a cell phone package that is missing the manual, or other collateral.
[src:check-weigher/check-weigher] Checkweighers are typically used on the incoming conveyor chain, and the output pre-packaging conveyor chain in a poultry processing plant.
[src:check-weigher/check-weigher] The bird is weighed when it comes onto the conveyor, then after processing and washing at the end, the network computer can determine whether or not the bird absorbed too much water, which as it is further processed, will be drained, making the bird under its target weight.
[src:check-weigher/check-weigher] A high speed conveyor scale can be used to change the pacing, or pitch of the products on the line by speeding, or slowing the product speed to change the distance between packs before reaching a different speed going into a conveyor machine that is boxing multiple packs into a box.
[src:check-weigher/check-weigher] The "pitch" is the measurement of the product as it comes down the conveyor line from leading edge to leading edge.
[src:check-weigher/check-weigher] A checkweigher can be used to count packs, and the aggregate (total) weight of the boxes going onto a pallet for shipment, including the ability to read each package's weight and cubic dimensions.
[src:check-weigher/check-weigher] The controller computer can print a shipping label and a bar-code label to identify the weight, the cubic dimensions, ship-to address, and other data for machine ID through the shipment of the product.
[src:check-weigher/check-weigher] A receiving checkweigher for the shipment can read the label with a bar code scanner, and determine if the shipment is as it was before the transportation carrier received it from the shipper's loading dock, and determine if a box is missing, or something was pilfered or broken in transit.
[src:check-weigher/check-weigher] Checkweighers are also used for Quality management.
[src:check-weigher/check-weigher] For instance, raw material for machining a bearing is weighed prior to beginning the process, and after the process, the quality inspector expects that a certain amount of metal was removed in the finishing process.
[src:check-weigher/check-weigher] The finished bearings are weighed by the checkweigher, and bearings over- or underweight are rejected for physical inspection.
[src:check-weigher/check-weigher] This is a benefit to the inspector, since he can have a high confidence that the ones not rejected are within machining tolerance.
[src:check-weigher/check-weigher] A common usage is for throttling plastic extruders such that a bottle used to package detergent meets that requirements of the finished packager.
[src:check-weigher/check-weigher] Quality management can use a checkweigher for Nondestructive testing to verify finished goods using common Evaluation methods to detect pieces missing from a "finished" product, such as grease from a bearing, or a missing roller within the housing.
[src:check-weigher/check-weigher] An industrial motion checkweigher can sort products from a fraction of a gram to many, many kilograms.
[src:check-weigher/check-weigher] In English units, is this from less than 100th of an ounce to as much as 500 lbs or more.
[src:check-weigher/check-weigher] Specialized checkweighers can weigh commercial aircraft, and even find their center-of-gravity.
[src:check-weigher/check-weigher] Checkweighers can operate at very high speeds, processing products weighing fractions of a gram at over 100m/m (meters per minute) and materials such as pharmaceuticals and 200 lb bags of produce at over 100fpm (feet per minute).
[src:check-weigher/check-weigher] They can be designed in many shapes and sizes, hung from ceilings, raised on mezzanines, operated in ovens or in refrigerators.
[src:check-weigher/check-weigher] Their conveying medium can be industrial belting, low-static belting, chains similar to bicycle chains (but much smaller), or interlocked chain belts of any width.
[src:check-weigher/check-weigher] They can have chain belts made of special materials, different polymers, metals, etc.
[src:check-weigher/check-weigher] Checkweighers are used in cleanrooms, mints (rolls of coins), dry atmosphere environments, wet environments, produce barns, food processing, drug processing, etc.
[src:check-weigher/check-weigher] Checkweighers are specified by the kind of environment, and the kind of cleaning will be used.
[src:check-weigher/check-weigher] Typically, a checkweigher for produce is made of mild steel, and one that will be cleaned with harsh chemicals, such as bleach, will be made with all stainless steel parts, even the load cells.
[src:check-weigher/check-weigher] These machines are labeled "full washdown", and must have every part and component specified to survive the washdown environment.
[src:check-weigher/check-weigher] Checkweighers are operated in some applications for extremely long periods of time- 24/7 year round.
[src:check-weigher/check-weigher] Generally, conveyor lines are not stopped unless there is maintenance required, or there is an emergency stop, called an E-stop.
[src:check-weigher/check-weigher] Checkweighers operating in high density conveyor lines may have numerous special equipments in their design to ensure that if an E-stop occurs, all power going to all motors is removed until the E-stop is cleared and reset.
